9 An Act relating to the Roofing Contractor
Registration Act; amending Section 4, Chapter 368,
10 O.S.L. 2025 (59 O.S. Supp. 2025, Section 1151.25a),
which relates to residential roofing endorsement;
11 updating statutory references; updating statutory
language; requiring certain continuing education to
12 be determined and approved by the Committee of
Roofing Examiners and the Construction Industries
13 Board; requiring certain valid endorsement to perform
certain work; providing certain exceptions; providing
14 an effective date; and declaring an emergency.
15
16
17 BE IT ENACTED BY THE PEOPLE OF THE STATE OF OKLAHOMA:
18 SECTION 1. AMENDATORY Section 4, Chapter 368, O.S.L.
19 2025 (59 O.S. Supp. 2025, Section 1151.25a), is amended to read as
20 follows:
21 Section 1151.25a. A. Except as otherwise provided in the
22 Roofing Contractor Registration Act, on and after the effective date
23 of this act beginning January 1, 2027, every roofing contractor,
24 except for those defined in subsection G of this section, offering
SB1873 HFLR Page 1
BOLD FACE denotes Committee Amendments.

1 to e ngage in or engaging in performing residential roofing
2 contractor work in this state shall be required to receive a
3 residential roofing endorsement. To receive a residential roofing
4 endorsement, the roofing contractor shall be required to take and
5 successfully pass a residential roofing examination approved under
6 the provisions of this act the Roofing Contractor Registration Act
7 with a minimum score of seventy percent (70%), and be in compliance
8 with all other provisions of this act the Roofing Contractor
9 Registration Act and rules before acting or being endorsed as a
10 residential roofing contractor. For applicants who have been
11 registered and in good standing with the Construction Industries
12 Board on the effective date of this act on January 1, 2027, there
13 shall be a twelve-month grandfathering-in period from the effective
14 date of this act January 1, 2027, to January 1, 2028, to either pass
15 the exam or complete an additional ten (10) hours of continuing
16 education credits approved in advance by the Committee of Roofing
17 Examiners to be granted a residential roofer endorsement. Any
18 applicant who has been registered, is in good standing with the
19 Board, and possesses a current commercial roofer endorsement on the
20 effective date of this act January 1, 2027, shall be exempt from the
21 residential roofing examination and additional ten (10) hours of
22 continuing education credits required to receive a residential
23 roofing endorsement.
24
SB1873 HFLR Page 2
BOLD FACE denotes Committee Amendments.

1 B. Examinations for a residential roofer endorsement shall be
2 uniform and practical in nature and sufficiently strict to test the
3 qualifications and fitness of the applicants for endorsement.
4 Examinations shall be in whole or in part in writing. Examinations
5 shall be offered at least monthly; dates, times, and locations shall
6 be determined by the registrar or third-party vendor with approval
7 of the registrar.
8 C. Any applicant initially failing to pass the examination
9 shall not be permitted to take another examination for a period of
10 thirty (30) days. Any applicant subsequently failing to pass the
11 examination shall not be permitted to take another examination for a
12 period of ninety (90) days. However, in a declared state of
13 emergency, the examination shall be available as often as possible
14 as determined by the registrar.
15 D. No residential roofer endorsement shall be renewed unless
16 the qualifying party has completed the required hours of continuing
17 education pursuant to subsection A of this section, as determined
18 and approved by the Committee of Roofing Examiners.
19 E. For all new applicants not registered and in good standing
20 with the Construction Industries Board on or prior to the effective
21 date of this act January 1, 2027, the Construction Industries Board
22 shall issue a residential roofer endorsement to qualifying
23 applicants no sooner than thirty (30) days from the date of
24 successful completion of the exam. New applicants shall not be
SB1873 HFLR Page 3
BOLD FACE denotes Committee Amendments.

1 allo wed to sell, offer, bid, inspect, or perform any residential
2 roofing contractor work in this state until a residential roofer
3 endorsement is issued.
4 F. For all applicants registered and in good standing with the
5 Construction Industries Board on or prior to the effective date of
6 this act January 1, 2027:
7 1. The residential roofer endorsement shall be issued
8 immediately upon compliance with the provisions of this section; and
9 2. Applicants shall be allowed to continue residential roofing
10 contractor work at all times during the residential roofer
11 endorsement application process, until January 1, 2028, when all
12 persons shall have a valid residential roofer endorsement to perform
13 residential roofing work unless otherwise exempted under the Roofing
14 Contractor Registration Act.
15 G. The residential roofing endorsement shall not apply to
16 roofing labor contractors who:
17 1. Only provide roofing construction labor services;
18 2. Are working directly for a registered roofing contractor
19 that possesses a residential roofing endorsement; and
20 3. Are not providing any materials.
21 SECTION 2. This act shall become effective July 1, 2026.
22 SECTION 3. It being immediately necessary for the preservation
23 of the public peace, health or safety, an emergency is hereby
24
